# Python + FastAPI Best Practices

## Type Hints (mandatory)
- All function parameters and return types must have type hints
- Use `X | None` (Python 3.10+ union syntax) — not `Optional[X]`
- Use `list[str]` not `List[str]` — built-in generics since 3.9
- Use `TypedDict` or Pydantic models for structured dicts — never `dict[str, Any]`
  > WHY: Type hints are machine-verified documentation. `Any` defeats the purpose.

## Async Discipline
- All I/O must be `async` — Supabase calls wrapped in `asyncio.to_thread(lambda: ...)`
- Never call blocking I/O directly in an async function
- `asyncio.to_thread` for synchronous SDK calls (supabase-py, pybreaker)
  > WHY: A single blocking call in an async route freezes the entire event loop.

## Naming Conventions
- `snake_case` for functions, variables, modules
- `PascalCase` for classes and Pydantic models
- `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for module-level constants
- Avoid abbreviations unless domain-standard (`qty`, `id`, `url` are fine)
  > WHY: Consistent with PEP 8 and Python ecosystem standards.

## Function Size
- Max ~25 lines per function — extract helpers for complex logic
- If a function needs a comment to explain what it does, split it
  > WHY: Small functions are testable in isolation and reviewable at a glance.

## FastAPI Patterns
- Use `Depends()` for dependency injection — never instantiate dependencies inside route handlers
- Use `Request` object to access `app.state` — do not use global variables in routers
- Return typed dicts or Pydantic models from endpoints — never bare `dict`
- Use `HTTPException` with specific status codes — never generic 500 for recoverable errors
  > WHY: Consistent error shapes let clients handle failures predictably.

## Error Handling
- Raise `HTTPException` at the router layer — not in service/model functions
- Service functions return typed results or raise domain exceptions
- Catch `ValidationError` from Pydantic at call sites — never swallow it silently
- Log structured errors — include `exc_info=True` for unexpected exceptions
  > WHY: Separation of concerns — routers translate exceptions, services raise them.

## Testing (pytest)
- Write the failing test first (TDD) for pure functions
- Test actual behavior — not implementation details
- Mock only external dependencies (Supabase, Gemini API, Redis) — never mock internal logic
- Use `pytest.raises` for expected exceptions — never `try/except` in tests
  > WHY: Tests that mock internal logic give false confidence and break on refactors.

## Constants
- Extract magic numbers to named constants at module level
- Example: `CACHE_TTL_SECONDS = 300` not `ex=300` inline
  > WHY: Constants are searchable, reusable, and self-documenting.

## Imports
- Use absolute imports within `app/` — no relative imports
- Group: stdlib → third-party → local (`app.*`) with blank lines between
- No wildcard imports (`from x import *`)
  > WHY: Absolute imports make refactoring safe and grep-friendly.

## Security
- Validate all external input at API boundary (Pydantic does this automatically)
- Never log API keys, tokens, passwords, or PII
- Sanitize error messages returned to clients — no stack traces in HTTP responses
  > WHY: Error details in responses are an information leak vector.

## Docstrings
- One-line `Args:` / `Returns:` block on public functions — nothing more
- No docstrings on private helpers or simple properties
- Never document what the code does — document why it does it that way
  > WHY: Good names document what. Docstrings document non-obvious constraints.
